         <abstract>
            <p>Prior to the 1982 passage of the Tax Equity and Fiscal Responsibility Act (TEFRA), there was a tax incentive for corporations to issue original issue discount bonds (OID) instead of par bonds because of the way the discount from the par value was amortized. Under TEFRA the discount has to be amortized on a constant interest rate instead of a straight-line basis. The firm will realize an advantage if it issues par bonds when the term structure is upsloping and zero-coupon when downsloping.</p>
         </abstract>
